task: Estimate the potential cost savings of using a local large language model (LLM) compared to cloud-based LLM services.
result:
Estimating potential cost savings of using a local large language model (LLM) compared to cloud-based LLM services depends primarily on usage volume, hardware costs, and operational expenses. Cloud LLMs typically charge on a pay-as-you-go basis, often around $0.0001 per token processed, leading to costs that scale linearly with usage. Local LLMs require significant upfront investment in hardware (GPUs, servers) and ongoing operational costs (electricity, maintenance), but marginal cost per query is very low.

A rough cost comparison example:
- Low usage (~1 million tokens/month): Cloud costs ~$100/month; local amortized hardware + OPEX ~$500/month → no savings.
- Medium usage (~10 million tokens/month): Cloud ~$1,000/month; local ~$500/month → ~50% savings.
- High usage (~100 million tokens/month): Cloud ~$10,000/month; local ~$500/month → ~95% savings.

Local LLMs become cost-effective primarily when usage is high and steady, allowing amortization of hardware costs and yielding significant savings over time. They also offer benefits in privacy and data control. Cloud LLMs remain attractive for low or variable usage due to zero upfront costs and scalability.

A hybrid approach—using local LLMs for baseline workloads and cloud LLMs for bursts—can optimize cost and performance.

In summary, organizations with high, consistent LLM workloads and privacy concerns can save substantially by deploying local LLMs, potentially reducing costs by up to 90% or more compared to cloud services over time.
